  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries and at international levels. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key features typically include:\n\n1. Financial institutions must:\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Verify customer identities\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Various national banking and financial regulations\n\n3. Regulations cover sectors like:\n- Banking\n- Securities\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Real estate\n- Gambling\n- Money transfer services\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecutions\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations aim to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illicit financial activities.",
